{"title_page": "Westerbeek", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=August 2015}}\n \n{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=ital |infobox caption=''Westerbeek''}} <!-- age of sail -->\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=\n|Ship caption=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=\n|Ship flag=\n|Ship name=\n|Ship owner=[[Dutch East India Company]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=1722\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=Wrecked 1742\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship tonnage=650 tons\n|Ship length={{convert|145|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam=\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship propulsion=\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship complement=\n|Ship armament=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n[[File:Lopranseidi View to Beinisvord.JPG|thumb|250px|The accident with ''Westerbeek'' happened here south of [[Lopransei\u00f0i]], the ship went between the four [[skerry|skerries]] and the steep sea cliff of Lopransei\u00f0i, just below the mountain [[Kirvi]].]]\n[[File:Ship Batavia 2.jpg|thumb|250px|''Batavia'', which is a copy of VOC ''Batavia'', which was a sister-ship of ''Westerbeek''. This ship was built from 1985 to 1995.]]\n'''''Westerbeek''''' was a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[Dutch East India Company|East India Company]] sailing ship, built in 1722 in [[Amsterdam]]. It was {{convert|145|ft|m}} long and 650 tons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.inghist.nl/Onderzoek/Projecten/DAS/detailVoyage/98038 |website=Historici |title=Details of voyage 7145.6 from Ceylon |department=The Dutch East India Company's shipping between the Netherlands and Asia 1595-1795}}</ref>\n\n== The accident ==\nThe ship was wrecked at [[Lopransei\u00f0i]] on the west coast of [[Su\u00f0uroy]], [[Faroe Islands]] on 2 September 1742. In those days it was necessary either to see the stars or the sun in order to navigate a ship, that is to know how far north or how far south the ship was. The crew of ''Westerbeek'' had not seen the sun because of fog for 11 days on the day of the accident, and because of that they went too far north. Too late they realized, that they were about to sail directly on land, and the ship went on land between four [[skerry|skerries]] and a sea cliff of [[Su\u00f0uroy]] on Lopransei\u00f0i. The accident happened on ''Westerbeek''{{'}}s 6th voyage from the [[Dutch East Indies]]. The captain of this voyage was Hermanus Schutten. The cargo was usually tea, coffee, pepper and other spices. The voyage to the East Indies could take up to one year, and often the ships were away from home several years, before returning home. \n\nOn 2 September 1742 around 10:30 at night ''Westerbeek'' ran on land south of Lopransei\u00f0i and sank between the four skerries and the island of [[Su\u00f0uroy]]. Ten of the men never had the time to leave their beds, as they were lying there because of illness. Three men died before the accident and were buried at sea. 81 of the men reached land after the accident, but one of them fell and died while attempting to climb the steep hill where the ship wrecked. They climbed on land through the broken mast of the ship. Then they tied together some oars and then some of the strongest of the men climbed up the hill to get help. Lopra was not a village at that time. The nearest populated places were [[V\u00e1gur]] and [[Sumba, Faroe Islands|Sumba]]. A few men went towards north and arrived to V\u00e1gur, where they got help. The legend says, that some people from V\u00e1gur were in the church and that the men from ''Westerbeek'' got help from them there.\n\n== The survivors and their further voyage ==\nResearch shows that all these 80 men were rescued. They then started the voyage from Su\u00f0uroy to [[T\u00f3rshavn]], the capital of the [[Faroe Islands]]. Today a journey from Su\u00f0uroy to T\u00f3rshavn takes two hours by ferry, but in 1742 they used Faroese rowing boats for transport, and it took several days with breaks in some of the islands, which they passed on their way to T\u00f3rshavn. A book has been published about the accident of ''Westerbeek'' and about the story of the men who survived. The book is written by Mathias Lassen. In the book he describes, that the 80 men traveled to T\u00f3rshavn in small rowing boats. They stopped in [[Sk\u00favoy]] but were not so welcome there, so they continued to the island of [[Sandoy]], where they were warmly welcomed in the village [[Sk\u00e1lav\u00edk]]. From Sk\u00e1lav\u00edk they continued to the village [[Kirkjub\u00f8ur]] in the south-western side of [[Streymoy]]. They were not welcome there and got neither food nor dry clothes, so they continued to T\u00f3rshavn. In T\u00f3rshavn two ships were ready to leave for [[Denmark]], and the plan was to get all these 80 men on board these two ships. But the captains of the two ships were afraid to take so many men with them and refused. Only 10 men were allowed to travel with them to Denmark. These were the last ships that year, so these 70 men had to stay all winter in the Faroe Islands, they stayed there for 9 months.\n\n== Faroese people descendant from the crew of Westerbeek ==\nThere are many stories about men from Westerbeek who stayed in the Faroes or sired children in the Faroes, but only a few of these stories can be verified. Joseph Gervording stayed in the Faroe Islands and married Marianna, the bailiff's daughter; they had three children, but no grandchildren. Then there was a woman from the village of [[Lamba (Faroe Islands)|Lamba]], the mother of twins fathered by one of the Westerbeek's crew, but both mother and children died in an [[avalanche]] in Ger\u00f0um in [[Klaksv\u00edk]] in 1745. Finally there was a girl from the island of [[V\u00e1gar]], who had a daughter with Berent Schouten, the Westerbeek's carpenter. The daughter, Sunneva Berentsdatter, is an ancestor of many Faroese.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery widths=\"200px\">\nFile:Su\u00f0uroy.westcoast.1.jpg|The ship went between the four skerries and the steep sea cliff of Lopransei\u00f0i, just below the mountain (under the bird).\nFile:Lopransei\u00f0i.1.jpg|\"Some of the strongest of the men climbed up the hill to get help\". \nFile:30-08 2009 Lopransnsei\u00f0i.jpg|The accident with Westerbeek happened here south of Lopransei\u00f0i\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.vocsite.nl/schepen/detail.html?id=11170 |website=De VOC Site |title=Westerbeek 1722 |language=Dutch}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://forum.faroe-islands.de/phpBB2/viewtopic.php?t=957 |website=Faroe Islands |department=Diskussionsforum F\u00e4r\u00f6er |title=Diskussion p\u00e5 de nordiske sprog om F\u00e6r\u00f8erne |language=Danish}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.bataviawerf.nl/en/bezoekinformatie.html |website=Bataviawerft |title=Maritime Museum of Bataviawerft}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.stamps.fo/Files/Billeder/stamps.fo/Myndir/Tak%20ni\u00f0ur%20PDF/Posta%20Stamps%20nr.%2026_UK.pdf| title= Posta Stamps-Batavia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Westerbeek}}\n[[Category:History of the Faroe Islands]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in the Faroe Islands]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of the Faroe Islands]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1742]]\n[[Category:Ships of the Dutch East India Company]]\n[[Category:Maritime accidents involving fog]]\n[[Category:Su\u00f0uroy]]\n[[Category:1720s ships]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=August 2015}}\n \n{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=ital |infobox caption=''Westerbeek''}} <!-- age of sail -->\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=\n|Ship caption=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=\n|Ship flag=\n|Ship name=\n|Ship owner=[[Dutch East India Company]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=1722\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=Wrecked 1742\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship tonnage=650 tons\n|Ship length={{convert|145|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam=\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship propulsion=\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship complement=\n|Ship armament=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n[[File:Lopranseidi View to Beinisvord.JPG|thumb|250px|The accident with ''Westerbeek'' happened here south of [[Lopransei\u00f0i]], the ship went between the four [[skerry|skerries]] and the steep sea cliff of Lopransei\u00f0i, just below the mountain [[Kirvi]].]]\n[[File:Ship Batavia 2.jpg|thumb|250px|''Batavia'', which is a copy of VOC ''Batavia'', which was a sister-ship of ''Westerbeek''. This ship was built from 1985 to 1995.]]\n'''''Westerbeek''''' was a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[Dutch East India Company|East India Company]] sailing ship, built in 1722 in [[Amsterdam]]. It was {{convert|145|ft|m}} long and 650 tons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.inghist.nl/Onderzoek/Projecten/DAS/detailVoyage/98038 |website=Historici |title=Details of voyage 7145.6 from Ceylon |department=The Dutch East India Company's shipping between the Netherlands and Asia 1595-1795}}</ref>\n\n== The accident ==\nThe ship was wrecked at [[Lopransei\u00f0i]] on the west coast of [[Su\u00f0uroy]], [[Faroe Islands]] on 2 September 1742. In those days it was necessary either to see the stars or the sun in order to navigate a ship, that is to know how far north or how far south the ship was. The crew of ''Westerbeek'' had not seen the sun because of fog for 11 days on the day of the accident, and because of that they went too far north. Too late they realized, that they were about to sail directly on land, and the ship went on land between four [[skerry|skerries]] and a sea cliff of [[Su\u00f0uroy]] on Lopransei\u00f0i. The accident happened on ''Westerbeek''{{'}}s 6th voyage from the [[Dutch East Indies]]. The captain of this voyage was Hermanus Schutten. The cargo was usually tea, coffee, pepper and other spices. The voyage to the East Indies could take up to one year, and often the ships were away from home several years, before returning home. \n\nOn 2 September 1742 around 10:30 at night ''Westerbeek'' ran on land south of Lopransei\u00f0i and sank between the four skerries and the island of [[Su\u00f0uroy]]. Ten of the men never had the time to leave their beds, as they were lying there because of illness. Three men died before the accident and were buried at sea. 81 of the men reached land after the accident, but one of them fell and died while attempting to climb the steep hill where the ship wrecked. They climbed on land through the broken mast of the ship. Then they tied together some oars and then some of the strongest of the men climbed up the hill to get help. Lopra was not a village at that time. The nearest populated places were [[V\u00e1gur]] and [[Sumba, Faroe Islands|Sumba]]. A few men went towards north and arrived to V\u00e1gur, where they got help. The legend says, that some people from V\u00e1gur were in the church and that the men from ''Westerbeek'' got help from them there.\n\n== The survivors and their further voyage ==\nResearch shows that all these 80 men were rescued. They then started the voyage from Su\u00f0uroy to [[T\u00f3rshavn]], the capital of the [[Faroe Islands]]. Today a journey from Su\u00f0uroy to T\u00f3rshavn takes two hours by ferry, but in 1742 they used Faroese rowing boats for transport, and it took several days with breaks in some of the islands, which they passed on their way to T\u00f3rshavn. A book has been published about the accident of ''Westerbeek'' and about the story of the men who survived. The book is written by Mathias Lassen. In the book he describes, that the 80 men traveled to T\u00f3rshavn in small rowing boats. They stopped in [[Sk\u00favoy]] but were not so welcome there, so they continued to the island of [[Sandoy]], where they were warmly welcomed in the village [[Sk\u00e1lav\u00edk]]. From Sk\u00e1lav\u00edk they continued to the village [[Kirkjub\u00f8ur]] in the south-western side of [[Streymoy]]. They were not welcome there and got neither food nor dry clothes, so they continued to T\u00f3rshavn. In T\u00f3rshavn two ships were ready to leave for [[Denmark]], and the plan was to get all these 80 men on board these two ships. But the captains of the two ships were afraid to take so many men with them and refused. Only 10 men were allowed to travel with them to Denmark. These were the last ships that year, so these 70 men had to stay all winter in the Faroe Islands, they stayed there for 9 months.\n\n== Faroese people descendant from the crew of Westerbeek ==\nThere are many stories about men from Westerbeek who stayed in the Faroes or sired children in the Faroes, but only a few of these stories can be verified. Joseph Gervording stayed in the Faroe Islands and married Marianna, the bailiff's daughter; they had three children, but no grandchildren. Then there was a woman from the village of [[Lamba]], the mother of twins fathered by one of the Westerbeek's crew, but both mother and children died in an [[avalanche]] in Ger\u00f0um in [[Klaksv\u00edk]] in 1745. Finally there was a girl from the island of [[V\u00e1gar]], who had a daughter with Berent Schouten, the Westerbeek's carpenter. The daughter, Sunneva Berentsdatter, is an ancestor of many Faroese.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery widths=\"200px\">\nFile:Su\u00f0uroy.westcoast.1.jpg|The ship went between the four skerries and the steep sea cliff of Lopransei\u00f0i, just below the mountain (under the bird).\nFile:Lopransei\u00f0i.1.jpg|\"Some of the strongest of the men climbed up the hill to get help\". \nFile:30-08 2009 Lopransnsei\u00f0i.jpg|The accident with Westerbeek happened here south of Lopransei\u00f0i\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.vocsite.nl/schepen/detail.html?id=11170 |website=De VOC Site |title=Westerbeek 1722 |language=Dutch}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://forum.faroe-islands.de/phpBB2/viewtopic.php?t=957 |website=Faroe Islands |department=Diskussionsforum F\u00e4r\u00f6er |title=Diskussion p\u00e5 de nordiske sprog om F\u00e6r\u00f8erne |language=Danish}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.bataviawerf.nl/en/bezoekinformatie.html |website=Bataviawerft |title=Maritime Museum of Bataviawerft}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.stamps.fo/Files/Billeder/stamps.fo/Myndir/Tak%20ni\u00f0ur%20PDF/Posta%20Stamps%20nr.%2026_UK.pdf| title= Posta Stamps-Batavia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Westerbeek}}\n[[Category:History of the Faroe Islands]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in the Faroe Islands]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of the Faroe Islands]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1742]]\n[[Category:Ships of the Dutch East India Company]]\n[[Category:Maritime accidents involving fog]]\n[[Category:Su\u00f0uroy]]\n[[Category:1720s ships]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLamba(link changed toLamba (Faroe Islands)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Westerbeek"}
{"title_page": "Lake Winnipesaukee mystery stone", "text_new": "[[File:Lake Winnipesaukee mystery stone at the New Hampshire Historical Society, Concord NH.jpg|thumb|250px|<center>Lake Winnipesaukee mystery stone<br>at the [[New Hampshire Historical Society]]</center>]]\n\n\nThe '''Lake Winnipesaukee mystery stone''' is an alleged [[out-of-place artifact]] (OOPArt) found in a town near [[Lake Winnipesaukee]] in [[New Hampshire]]. The stone's age, purpose and origin are unknown.<ref name=\"nhhistory\" />\n\nThe stone is about {{convert|4|in}} long and {{convert|2.5|in}} thick, dark and egg-shaped, bearing a variety of carved symbols.<ref name=\"nhhistory\" /> Carvings on one side of the stone show an ear of [[Maize|corn]] and several other figures. The other side is more abstract, featuring inverted arrows, a moon shape, some dots and a spiral.<ref name=\"weird\" />\n\nA hole goes through the stone from top to bottom, seemingly bored from both ends with different size bits ({{convert|1/8|inch}} at the top and {{convert|3/8|in}} at the bottom).<ref name=\"weird\">{{cite book |first=Joseph A. |last=Citro |year=2005 |publisher=[[Sterling Publishing]] |isbn=1402733305 |title=Joe Citro's weird New England : your travel guide to New England's local legends and best kept secrets|page=[https://archive.org/details/weirdnewenglandw00jose/page/33 33]|url=https://archive.org/details/weirdnewenglandw00jose|url-access=registration |quote=Lake Winnipesaukee. }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe stone was reportedly found in 1872 in [[Meredith, New Hampshire]], by workers digging a hole for a fence post. Seneca Ladd, a Meredith businessman who hired the workers, was given credit for the discovery.<ref name=\"nhhistory\" /> In 1892, upon Ladd's death, the stone passed to Frances Ladd Coe of Center Harbor, one of his daughters. In 1927, she donated the stone to the [[New Hampshire Historical Society]].<ref name=\"nhhistory\" />\n\nThe stone is currently on exhibit at the [[New Hampshire Historical Society|Museum of New Hampshire History]].<ref name=\"nhhistory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nhhistory.org/museumexhibits/mysterystone/mysterystone.htm |title=The Mystery Stone |publisher=New Hampshire Historical Society |accessdate=2010-10-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100914204903/http://www.nhhistory.org/museumexhibits/mysterystone/mysterystone.htm |archivedate=2010-09-14 }}</ref><ref name=\"Hill\">{{cite news |url=https://www.ancient-origins.net/unexplained-phenomena/out-place-artifact-mysterious-stone-egg-lake-winnipesaukee-003622?fbclid=IwAR1Ftv9ERFYMTVq1iiSQBd_jiHlD42JBdA6_jiu3-P5wr2CJYFwHQtk2sjg |date=19 August 2015 |first1=Bryan |last1=Hill |title=Out of Place Artifact: The Mysterious Stone Egg of Lake Winnipesaukee |accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Analysis and interpretation==\nA contemporary source suggested that the stone \"commemorates a treaty between two tribes\".<ref name=\"an1872\">Author unknown (1872). The American Naturalist, November 1872.</ref> Another writer later suggested that it is a [[thunderstone (folklore)|thunderstone]]. With the somewhat limited understanding of the day, the letter said that thunderstones \"always present the appearance of having been machined or hand-worked: frequently they come from deep in the earth, embedded in lumps of clay, or even surrounded by solid rock or coral\".<ref name=\"thunderstone\">Author unknown (1931). Letter to the New Hampshire Historical Society, 1931.</ref>\n \nIn 1994, a [[borescope]] analysis of the stone's holes was performed. State archaeologist Richard Boisvert later suggested that the holes had the appearance of having been drilled by power tools from the 19th or 20th century: <blockquote>\"I've seen a number of holes bored in stone with technology that you would associate with [[prehistory|prehistoric]] North America. There's a certain amount of unevenness ... and this hole was extremely regular throughout. What we did not see was variations that would be consistent with something that was several hundred years old.\"<ref name=\"cbsnews\" /></blockquote>\n\nScratches in the lower bore suggest it was placed on a metal shaft and removed several times.<ref name=\"cbsnews\">{{cite web| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/07/21/national/main1826460.shtml| date=July 23, 2006| title=New England's 'Mystery Stone': New Hampshire Displays Unexplained Artifact 134 Years Later|first=James M. |last= Klatell| publisher=Associated Press| accessdate=2010-10-01}}</ref>\n\nAnalysis has concluded the stone is a type of [[quartzite]].<ref>[https://newengland.com/today/living/new-england-history/mystery-stone-of-lake-winnipesaukee/ New England.com: \"Mystery Stone\"]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Coord|43|12|25|N|71|32|08|W|type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lake Winnipesaukee Mystery Stone}}\n[[Category:Pseudoarchaeology]]\n[[Category:Out-of-place artifacts]]\n[[Category:1872 in the United States]]\n[[Category:Lake Winnipesaukee|Mystery Stone]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Lake Winnipesaukee mystery stone at the New Hampshire Historical Society, Concord NH.jpg|thumb|250px|<center>Lake Winnipesaukee mystery stone<br>at the [[New Hampshire Historical Society]]</center>]]\n\n\nThe '''Lake Winnipesaukee mystery stone''' is an alleged [[out-of-place artifact]] (OOPArt) found in a town near [[Lake Winnipesaukee]] in [[New Hampshire]]. The stone's age, purpose and origin are unknown.<ref name=\"nhhistory\" />\n\nThe stone is about {{convert|4|in}} long and {{convert|2.5|in}} thick, dark and egg-shaped, bearing a variety of carved symbols.<ref name=\"nhhistory\" /> Carvings on one side of the stone show an ear of [[Maize|corn]] and several other figures. The other side is more abstract, featuring inverted arrows, a moon shape, some dots and a spiral.<ref name=\"weird\" />\n\nA hole goes through the stone from top to bottom, seemingly bored from both ends with different size bits ({{convert|1/8|inch}} at the top and {{convert|3/8|in}} at the bottom).<ref name=\"weird\">{{cite book |first=Joseph A. |last=Citro |year=2005 |publisher=[[Sterling Publishing]] |isbn=1402733305 |title=Joe Citro's weird New England : your travel guide to New England's local legends and best kept secrets|page=[https://archive.org/details/weirdnewenglandw00jose/page/33 33]|url=https://archive.org/details/weirdnewenglandw00jose|url-access=registration |quote=Lake Winnipesaukee. }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe stone was reportedly found in 1872 in [[Meredith, New Hampshire]], by workers digging a hole for a fence post. Seneca Ladd, a Meredith businessman who hired the workers, was given credit for the discovery.<ref name=\"nhhistory\" /> In 1892, upon Ladd's death, the stone passed to Frances Ladd Coe of Center Harbor, one of his daughters. In 1927, she donated the stone to the [[New Hampshire Historical Society]].<ref name=\"nhhistory\" />\n\nThe stone is currently on exhibit at the [[New Hampshire Historical Society|Museum of New Hampshire History]].<ref name=\"nhhistory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nhhistory.org/museumexhibits/mysterystone/mysterystone.htm |title=The Mystery Stone |publisher=New Hampshire Historical Society |accessdate=2010-10-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100914204903/http://www.nhhistory.org/museumexhibits/mysterystone/mysterystone.htm |archivedate=2010-09-14 }}</ref>\n\n==Analysis and interpretation==\nA contemporary source suggested that the stone \"commemorates a treaty between two tribes\".<ref name=\"an1872\">Author unknown (1872). The American Naturalist, November 1872.</ref> Another writer later suggested that it is a [[thunderstone (folklore)|thunderstone]]. With the somewhat limited understanding of the day, the letter said that thunderstones \"always present the appearance of having been machined or hand-worked: frequently they come from deep in the earth, embedded in lumps of clay, or even surrounded by solid rock or coral\".<ref name=\"thunderstone\">Author unknown (1931). Letter to the New Hampshire Historical Society, 1931.</ref>\n \nIn 1994, a [[borescope]] analysis of the stone's holes was performed. State archaeologist Richard Boisvert later suggested that the holes had the appearance of having been drilled by power tools from the 19th or 20th century: <blockquote>\"I've seen a number of holes bored in stone with technology that you would associate with [[prehistory|prehistoric]] North America. There's a certain amount of unevenness ... and this hole was extremely regular throughout. What we did not see was variations that would be consistent with something that was several hundred years old.\"<ref name=\"cbsnews\" /></blockquote>\n\nScratches in the lower bore suggest it was placed on a metal shaft and removed several times.<ref name=\"cbsnews\">{{cite web| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/07/21/national/main1826460.shtml| date=July 23, 2006| title=New England's 'Mystery Stone': New Hampshire Displays Unexplained Artifact 134 Years Later|first=James M. |last= Klatell| publisher=Associated Press| accessdate=2010-10-01}}</ref>\n\nAnalysis has concluded the stone is a type of [[quartzite]].<ref>[https://newengland.com/today/living/new-england-history/mystery-stone-of-lake-winnipesaukee/ New England.com: \"Mystery Stone\"]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Coord|43|12|25|N|71|32|08|W|type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lake Winnipesaukee Mystery Stone}}\n[[Category:Pseudoarchaeology]]\n[[Category:Out-of-place artifacts]]\n[[Category:1872 in the United States]]\n[[Category:Lake Winnipesaukee|Mystery Stone]]\n", "name_user": "7&6=thirteen", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_Winnipesaukee_mystery_stone"}
